‎02-13-2012 06:57 AM

Hi Gail!  Welcome to the Step Out community boards!

 

In 2009 I formed a small walk team for Michigan's Step Out Walk after being diagnosed with Type 2 diabetes. The team name at the time was "Stompin' Out Diabetes"....pretty generic, but it said what I wanted it to say. I gathered a handful of friends and family to walk with me, and raised just over $1,000 that first year.  How could we possibly know that one of our walkers, Jack Schoenbeck, would pass away from diabetes complications just weeks before the walk?  Jack was a beloved firefighter and fire instructor here in our community and his death was devastating to so many people. In 2009 we walked in his memory.

 

For 2010 I renamed the team "Jack's Jaywalkers" to honor our dear friend. With just over 20 walkers, Jack's Jaywalkers proudly walked and raised over $6,000 for the event. We held a handful of fun events in 2010 and partnered up with our local fire stations and businesses to publicize our fundraising efforts.

 

Last year Jack's Jaywalkers was back with a vengeance and raised almost $11,000 for our efforts. We were so proud to receive the top team honors here in Michigan, and it was such a fantastic tribute to Jack. His wife Ann accepted the team award at the annual awards ceremony - it was a bittersweet moment.

 

This year the team is gearing up for another round of fundraising efforts in Jack's name, and for the ADA.

 

We wear our team name proudly.

 

Kathy

 

 

Kathy Ryan
2012 Event Chair, Step Out: Walk to Stop Diabetes-Michigan
2009-11 Family/Friends Team Captain, Jack's Jaywalkers
2012 Corporate Team Captain, GHSP

‎02-13-2012 02:07 PM

Hi all, My Daughter's team is named " Sarah's Too Sweet Team". We have used the same name for the last several years and even have a banner made to use for our yearly team picture. Obviously, the name is a "pun" on her Type 1 diabetes but also, as she is a kid who has a very sweet demeanor.  We use the team picture in our thank you postcards that we send each year, telling all our sponsors how the team did as a whole. We think its a nice way to say thank you and to make it real to those folks who may not see the energy or effort that goes into the annual walks.

 

Hope this helps!  Ellen

‎02-16-2012 03:54 PM

Our team name has been "Madison's Prayer" for 11 years.

When my daughter was diagnosed at age 5, she wanted to participate in her first walk just a month later.

Her greatest prayer, both then and now, is for a cure for diabetes.  Even though she very rarely goes by "Madison" (except maybe when she has not cleaned her room or something along those lines...), and she much prefers to be called Madi, she has never wanted to change her team name.  The walk, and all that it means to her, is a very major influence in her life.  As a result, it means the world to me was well

Wendy

I'm captain of a corporate team named "[Company Name] Pacesetters"

 

(sorry for the generic use of [Company Name], but I don't know if the usage guidelines for this site would allow me to use my actual company name...)

 

I know it's a bit generic, but I liked the use of "Pacesetters" to challenge our team members to truly BE pacesetters in walking, fundraising and helping to spread awareness of diabetes. And we have become pacesetters - over the last 20 years or so, we've consistently been in the top ten teams, with at least one or two members in the top ten individual fundrasiers.
